            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Hi, feel free to mark this as off-topic, but the referenced issue related to the tree-sitter parser distribution strategy is locked, so I can't comment there directly.\n\nI'm not sure if Neovim still uses LuaRocks during the build step; I've been pretty out of touch with the project and the code for a couple of years now. However, I'm wondering how viable it would be for you to consider (perhaps) bundling using something like the [binary rocks](https://lux.lumen-labs.org/rocks-binaries/) from the lumen-oss organization. We have all the tree-sitter parsers pre-compiled there for the main operating systems and multiple architectures, along with their queries embedded from nvim-treesitter, so it could save some initial work, even if it's just for ideas or reference.\n\nJust in case, the parser data is obtained from [tree-sitter-parser.json](https://github.com/lumen-oss/nurr/blob/main/tree-sitter-parsers.json) in the repository; adding new parsers is simple and updates are automated. I know that some people use their parsers this way, and my own setup also pulls parsers this way on both Linux and macOS devices I have, and I've never had problems with `libc` or anything similar, so it might be worth taking a look.",
